til 1670","about 1658":"omkring 1658","from 1658 to 1668":"fra 1658 til 1668","1650":"1650","28 February 1669":"28. februar 1669","about 1620":"omkring 1620","from about 1647 to 1648":"fra omkring 1647 til 1648","1648":"1648","1658":"1658","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1623–28 February 1669":"1623–28 februari 1669","1623–1669":"1623–1669","–Female":"Overleden","1634–Female":"1634–Overleden","1658–Female":"1658–Overleden","1660–Male":"1660–Overleden","1650–1723":"1650–1723","–1648":"–1648","1601–Female":"1601–Overleden","from about 1650 to 1660":"van circa 1650 to 1660","1660":"1660","before 1658":"vóór 1658","1723":"1723","1623":"1623","1601":"1601","1634":"1634","from about 1660 to 1670":"van circa 1660 to 1670","about 1658":"circa 1658","from 1658 to 1668":"van 1658 to 1668","1650":"1650","28 February 1669":"28 februari 1669","about 1620":"circa 1620","from about 1647 to 1648":"van circa 1647 to 1648","1648":"1648","1658":"1658","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1623–28 February 1669":"1623–28 February 1669","1623–1669":"1623–1669","–Female":"Deceased","1634–Female":"1634–Deceased","1658–Female":"1658–Deceased","1660–Male":"1660–Deceased","1650–1723":"1650–1723","–1648":"–1648","1601–Female":"1601–Deceased","from about 1650 to 1660":"from about 1650 to 1660","1660":"1660","before 1658":"before 1658","1723":"1723","1623":"1623","1601":"1601","1634":"1634","from about 1660 to 1670":"from about 1660 to 1670","about 1658":"about 1658","from 1658 to 1668":"from 1658 to 1668","1650":"1650","28 February 1669":"28 February 1669","about 1620":"about 1620","from about 1647 to 1648":"from about 1647 to 1648","1648":"1648","1658":"1658","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fraser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: apparently a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>fraser(e)</i>, <i>fresere</i> ‘strawberry plant’. <i>Fresel</i> and <i>Frisel</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, are early variants of the Fraser surname, the modern Gaelicized form of which is <b>Friseal</b>. See   Frizzell  . The crest on the Scottish family's coat of arms takes the form of a strawberry plant, but its antiquity is unknown. Claims of a habitational derivation, in particular from a place called la Frézelière in Anjou (France), are attractive but they lack verifiable evidence.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: There are two clans Fraser in Scotland, with common ancestry going back to Simon Fraser of Keith in East Lothian, who lived in the 12th century. One of these clans has its seat at Philorth Castle (subsequently re-named Cairnbulg) on the northeast coast of Scotland. Sir Alexander Fraser, 8th laird of Philorth (<i>c.</i> 1536–1623) converted the fishing village of Faithlie into the burgh of Fraserburgh in the 1590s. The other clan is Fraser of Lovat, associated mainly with the city of Inverness are. They are descended from Simon Fraser, a younger son, who lived in the early 14th century. In Gaelic, the head of Clan Fraser of Lovat is known as <i>Mac Shimi</i> ‘son of Simon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Frayser","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasure","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazer","meanings":["Variant of   Fraser  , associated chiefly with northern Ireland."]},{"name":"Fraizer","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frashier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Fraiser","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frizzell","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Old French <i>fresel</i>, <i>frisel</i> ‘lace, ribbon, braid, brooch, frill, ruff’, for someone with an ornate style of dress, or ‘object of little value’ (a diminutive of <i>frese</i>, of ancient Germanic origin).","Scottish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, an alternative form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazier","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Fraser  .","Americanized form of French <b>Frégeau</b> (see   Fregeau  )."]},{"name":"Frasher","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Fratzscher</b> (see   Frutchey  )."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Fraser 7th of Foyers was born in 1623, in Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom a